The N,SCDs based fluorescent sensing platform is applied for Cr (VI) detection in real drinking water samples (Taihu and tap water). As Figs. S8(a) and S9(a) indicated, the fluorescence intensity of N,SCDs in both two samples decreased with the increasing concentration of Cr (VI). In addition, in real water samples, good linear relationships between fluorescence intensity of N,SCDs and the concentration of Cr (VI) from 1 to 40μM were obtained (the insets of Figs. S8(b) and S9(b)respectively). The limits of detection in Taihu and tap water samples were 0.73μM and 0.61μM in terms of 3 times signal-to-noise ratio. Clearly, it is indicated that these LODs are lower than the guideline limit of the WHO [48]. Moreover, the recovery experiments were performed using a standard addition method. As shown in Table 2
                        , the sample recoveries are in the range of 92–107% in Taihu water, while the relative standard deviations (RSDs) are between 2.4% and 4.2%. Meanwhile, as for tap water (Table 3
                        ), the recoveries are estimated to be 97–106%, together with the RSD varied from 1.9–3.6%. In a word, using N,SCDs to detect Cr (VI) in real water is not only easy and low-cost, but also highly sensitive and accurate. Thus, N,SCDs is promising in monitoring the amount of Cr (VI) in environmental water fields.
